===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*sed-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|setten|}}, from {{inh|en|ang|settan}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*sattjan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*satjanÄ…}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*sodÃ©yeti}}, causative of {{m|ine-pro|*sed-||to sit}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|~s|~ting|~|+,~ten<l:dialectal>}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[put]] (something) down, to [[rest]].
#: {{syn|en|put|lay|set down}}
#: {{ant|en|pick up}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Set''' the [[tray]] there.}}
#: {{ux|en|He helped his mother '''set''' the table for lunch.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To attach or affix (something) to something else, or in or upon a certain place.
#: {{ux|en|I have '''set''' my heart on running the marathon.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Genesis|4|15|passage=The Lord '''set''' a mark upon Cain.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To put in a specified condition or state; to cause to be.
#* {{RQ:KJV|Deuteronomy|28|1|passage=The Lord thy God will '''set''' thee on high.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|10|35|passage=I am come to '''set''' a man at variance against his father, and the daughter against her mother.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1827|author=w:Samuel Taylor Coleridge|title=Hamlet
|passage=Every incident '''sets''' him thinking.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[start]] (a [[fire]]).
#: {{syn|en|light}}
#: {{ant|en|extinguish|put out|quench}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|dated}} To cause to stop or stick; to obstruct; to fasten to a spot.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' a coach in the mud}}
# {{senseid|en|determine}}{{lb|en|transitive}} To [[determine]] or [[settle]].
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' the rent}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[adjust]].
#: {{ux|en|I '''set''' the alarm at 6 a.m.}}  (i.e. I programmed it at that hour to go off at a later time)
#: {{ux|en|I '''set''' the alarm for 6 a.m.}}  (i.e. I programmed it earlier to go off at that hour.)
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To punch (a [[nail]]) into [[wood]] so that its head is below the surface.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To arrange with [[dish]]es and [[cutlery]], to [[set the table]].
#: {{ux|en|Please '''set''' the table for our guests.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[introduce]] or [[describe]].
#: {{ux|en|Iâ€™ll tell you what happened, but first let me '''set''' the scene.}}
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|chapter=II|passage=An incident which happened about this time will '''set''' the characters of these two lads more fairly before the discerning reader than is in the power of the longest dissertation.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[locate]] (a play, etc.); to assign a [[backdrop]] to, geographically or temporally.
#: {{ux|en|He says he will '''set''' his next film in France.}}
#: {{ux|en|Her debut novel is '''set''' during the U.S. Civil War.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[compile]], to make (a puzzle or challenge).
#: {{ux|en|This crossword was '''set''' by Araucaria.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To prepare (a stage or film set).
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To fit (someone) up in a situation. <!-- Same as "set the scene" or rather "prepare"? An example would help.-->
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To arrange (type).
#: {{syn|en|typeset}}
#: {{ux|en|It was a complex page, but he '''set''' it quickly.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[devise]] and [[assign]] (work) to.
#: {{ux|en|The teacher '''set''' her students the task of drawing a foot.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|volleyball}} To direct (the ball) to a teammate for an attack.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[solidify]].
#: {{ux|en|The glue '''sets''' in five minutes.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To render stiff or solid; especially, to convert into curd; to curdle.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' milk for cheese}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of a heavenly body, to disappear below the [[horizon]] of a planet, etc, as the latter rotates.<!--not necessarily Earth: on the moon, the Earth can be seen to set-->
#: {{ux|en|The moon '''sets''' at eight o'clock tonight.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|bridge}} To [[defeat]] a [[contract]].
# {{lb|en|obsolete|now followed by "out", as in [[set out]]}} To begin to move; to [[go forth]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|text=The king is '''set''' from London, and the scene is now transported, gentles, to Southampton}}
