|passage=At Eastertime one year, she helped him to '''set''' potatoes.}}
# To become [[fixed]] or [[rigid]]; to be [[fastened]].
# To have a certain direction of motion; to flow; to move on; to tend.
#: {{ux|en|The current '''sets''' to the north; the tide '''sets''' to the windward.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|country dancing}} To acknowledge a dancing partner by facing him or her and moving first to one side and then to the other, while she or he does the opposite.
#: {{ux|en|'''Set''' to partners! was the next instruction from the caller.}}
# To place or fix in a [[setting]].
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' a precious stone in a border of metal}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' glass in a sash}}
#* {{RQ:Dryden Spanish Fryar|58|And him too rich a jewel to be '''set''' / In vulgar metal for a vulgar use.}}
# To put in order in a particular manner; to prepare.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' (that is, to hone) a razor}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' a saw}}
# To extend and bring into position; to spread.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' the sails of a ship}}
# To give a pitch to, as a tune; to start by fixing the keynote.
#* {{RQ:Fielding Joseph Andrews|volume=I|chapter=Here Joseph Andrews Writ a Letter to His Sister Pamela|page=25|passage={{...}} I Å¿hould be very vvilling to be his Clerk; for vvhich you knovv I am qualified, being able to read, and to '''Å¿et''' a PÅ¿alm.}}
# To reduce from a dislocated or fractured state.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' a broken bone}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|now|dialectal}} To [[sit]] or [[lie]] (easily etc.) on the [[stomach]]; to be [[digested]] in a certain manner.<!--OED2 5d.-->
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=1917-02-12|title=If You Knew What Foods?|title_plain=advertisement|journal=w:[[The Independent (New York City)|The Independent]]|volume=59|issue=3558|location=New York|publisher=Independent Corporation|page=280|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sim_independent_1917-02-12_89_3558/page/280/mode/2up?q=set|passage=If you also knew how to combine foodsâ€”that is, what foods eaten together â€œ'''set''' well,â€ you need never have indigestion, constipation or any of the headachy, stomachachy ills they lead to.}}
# {{lb|en|masonry}} To lower into place and fix solidly, as the blocks of cut stone in a structure.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To wager in gambling; to risk.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Richard 3|V|iv|passage=I have '''set''' my life upon a cast, / And I will stand the hazard of the die.}}
# To adorn with something infixed or affixed; to stud; to variegate with objects placed here and there.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Fables|The Flower and the Leaf
|passage=High on their heads, with jewels richly '''set''', / Each lady wore a radiant coronet.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1815|author=w:William Wordsworth|title=Poems of the Imagination
|passage=pastoral dales thin '''set''' with modern farms}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To value; to rate; used with ''at''.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-2|V|ii|passage=Be you contented, wearing now the garland, / To have a son '''set''' your decrees at naught.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|I|iv|passage=I do not '''set''' my life at a pin's fee.}}
# To establish as a rule; to furnish; to prescribe; to assign.
#: {{ux|en|to '''set''' a good example}}
# {{lb|en|Scotland}} To suit; to become.
#: {{ux|en|It '''sets''' him ill.}}
# To cause (a domestic fowl) to sit on eggs to brood.
#: {{uxi|en|To '''set''' a hen.}}

=====Usage notes=====
Originally, ''set'' specifically served as the causative of ''sit'', and this relationship is still reflected in several of the above senses. However, as with many such pairs, the correspondence has mostly deteriorated, with new senses of ''sit'' no longer being accompanied with a like sense of ''set''; notably, there are now transitive senses of ''sit'' and intransitive senses of ''set''. Compare {{m|en|rise}} and {{m|en|raise}}, whose senses are almost all intransitive and transitive counterparts, respectively.

