===Etymology 4===
From {{der|en|enm|set}}, {{m|enm|sete}}, {{m|enm|sette||that which is set, the act of setting, seat}}, from {{der|en|ang|set||setting, seat, a place where people remain, habitation, camp, entrenchment, a place where animals are kept, stall, fold}} and {{der|en|ang|seten||a set, shoot, slip, branch; a nursery, plantation; that which is planted or set; a cultivated place; planting, cultivation; a setting, putting; a stopping; occupied land}}, related to {{cog|ang|settan||to set}}. Compare {{cog|gml|gesette||a set, suite}}, {{cog|ang|gesetl||assembly}}. According to Skeat, in senses denoting a group of things or persons, representing an alteration of {{m|en|sept}}, from {{der|en|fro|sette||a religious sect}}, from {{der|en|ML.|secta||retinue}}, from {{der|en|la|secta||a faction}}. See {{l|en|sect}}. It is quite possible that the modern word is more of a merger between both, however.

